        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-18T15:57:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Not expressing a preference one way or another, just wondering: is it worth doing something different for non-Android Linux when the higher-level libcap interface is defunct/obsolete/withdrawn/whatever, and we have to have the raw syscall-based interface for Android anyway?",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6978483c_c24600cc",
        "filename": "handler/linux/exception_handler_server.cc",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 111,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-18T23:21:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It looks like more libcap support might be eventually coming to Android:\nhttps://android.googlesource.com/platform/external/libcap/\n\nBut on the other hand, LINUX_CAPABILITY_VERSION_3 is old enough I\u0027m guessing we can generally expect to be using it, reducing the need for libcap to handle different versions for us. I\u0027ve stashed the libcap version for now.",
      "parentUuid": "24ee7fda_265fbfce",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "06520053_7407c446",
        "filename": "util/linux/exception_handler_client.cc",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 80,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-18T15:57:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This seems weird, I don’t recall having to do this on the sender’s side at all.",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "60e223c7_b7e5f4c3",
        "filename": "util/linux/exception_handler_client.cc",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 80,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-18T23:21:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Documentation says the sender has to specify it\u0027s credentials, which are checked by the kernel. The sender can specify another process\u0027 credentials if it has CAP_SYS_ADMIN.\n\nIf I don\u0027t set this, sendmsg returns EPERM.\n\nThe sender doesn\u0027t have to set anything if we use SO_PEERCRED, but that returns the credentials of whatever process created the socket, which might not always be the sender.",
      "parentUuid": "06520053_7407c446",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "97e81c6a_11df595d",
        "filename": "util/linux/exception_handler_client.cc",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 80,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-19T04:01:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Documentation says the sender has to specify it\u0027s credentials, which are checked by the kernel. The sender can specify another process\u0027 credentials if it has CAP_SYS_ADMIN.\n\u003e \n\u003e If I don\u0027t set this, sendmsg returns EPERM.\n\u003e \n\u003e The sender doesn\u0027t have to set anything if we use SO_PEERCRED, but that returns the credentials of whatever process created the socket, which might not always be the sender.\n\nSO_PEERCRED must be what I was recalling, then.\n\nShould the uid and gid be getting the euid and egid instead? Can\u0027t check the server implementation right now.\n\nProvided that this is kernel-checked and that there\u0027s no way to avoid sending this over, it sounds like you\u0027ve done the right thing. Thanks!",
      "parentUuid": "60e223c7_b7e5f4c3",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "beef1476_ee7fee37",
        "filename": "util/linux/exception_handler_client.cc",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 80,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-19T19:51:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "euid/egid probably makes more sense to look at, so I\u0027ve used them, but I don\u0027t think it will end up making a practical difference. sendmsg allows any of uid/euid/suid to be specified. The server cares about this for the purposes of ptrace-attaching, but it looks like (I haven\u0027t verified) uid/euid/suid for the victim process all need to be the same anyways:\nhttp://elixir.free-electrons.com/linux/latest/source/kernel/ptrace.c#L312",
      "parentUuid": "97e81c6a_11df595d",
      "revId": "c9150c0a4748281e5e3ae8c6e267cc842a729bcb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    }
